<h1 id="soil-site-observation-and-pit-characterisation">Soil Site
Observation and Pit Characterisation</h1>
<h2 id="field-collection-3">Field collection</h2>
<h3 id="pre-requisites-3">Pre-requisites</h3>
<p>Pre-requisites for completing this protocol:</p>
<ul>
<li><p>Before commencing the survey, the Plot Layout and Selection
Module must be completed.</p></li>
<li><p>The <a href="https://linked.data.gov.au/def/nrm/1ff9e97c-3bdd-44c9-bdd3-401fa31c0b32">Plot Description Module</a> must be completed before or during or
the protocol. The <a href="https://linked.data.gov.au/def/nrm/1ff9e97c-3bdd-44c9-bdd3-401fa31c0b32">Plot Description Module</a> is best completed by personnel
familiar with describing the landforms and vegetation
communities.</p></li>
<li><p>The protocol involves the collection and transportation of soil
samples, requiring appropriate scientific permits and approvals.
Movement of soil samples may involve obtaining a biosecurity permit,
which can entail safe packaging, proper labelling, and documentation.
Check with the local authority for specific requirements.</p></li>
</ul>
<h3 id="time-requirements-3">Time requirements</h3>
<p>Survey time requirements will vary depending on the number and
experience of personnel, their familiarity with the landform features
and soils of the project area, soil type and depth. As a general
guide:</p>
<ul>
<li><p>Allow 15 minutes to collect and record soil site
observations.</p></li>
<li><p>Allow between 2–3 hours for digging of the soil pit.</p></li>
<li><p>Allow between 2–3 hours to describe soil profile, collect
samples, and record the information.</p></li>
</ul>
<h3 id="personnel-requirements-3">Personnel requirements</h3>
<p>Number of personnel and skills:</p>
<ul>
<li><p>Completing the Soil site observation and pit characterisation
protocol is best conducted with two personnel. Initially, one surveyor
can be collecting soil site observation data directly into the app while
the other surveyor commences digging of the soil pit. Digging of the
soil pit, particularly where soils are deep or difficult to dig, should
be shared between personnel. Once the soil pit has been completed, one
surveyor can be describing the soil profile and collecting samples as
the other records the data directly into the app. </p></li>
<li><p>Soil site observation and soil characterisation should be
conducted by a pedologist, soil scientist, or experienced soil
surveyor.</p></li>
<li><p>Personnel should be familiar with landform, land surface and soil
attributes including but not limited to landform patterns and elements,
lithology, microrelief, erosion, drainage, soil surface conditions,
horizons features, field soil texture, soil classification.</p></li>
<li><p>Personnel should be familiar with or can familiarise themselves
with key features in the project area that will assist in an
understanding and interpretation of land surfaces and soil
characterisation, including the topography, geology and geomorphology,
and any previous soil mapping conducted within or in proximity to the
area.</p></li>
</ul>"""^^rdf:HTML ;
