    tern:equipment """<h3 id="equipment-3">Equipment</h3>
<ul>
<li><p>Mobile device (tablet/phone) with the Monitor app
pre-loaded</p></li>
<li><p>GNSS receiver capable of achieving &lt;30 cm accuracy (e.g.
Trimble R1 or DA2), hand-held GPS or device built-in GPS (least
preferred)</p></li>
<li><p>DSLR camera and micro SD card(s) (optional)</p></li>
<li><p>Clinometer (or suitable app)</p></li>
<li><p>Large tools (long-handled shovel, spade, mattock,
crowbar)</p></li>
<li><p>Soil auger (Jarrett hand auger 75 mm) with 10 cm depths marked on
the handle</p></li>
<li><p>Small tools (trowel, geo pick, lump hammer, secateurs, wire
scrubbing brush, paint brush)</p></li>
<li><p>Ground sheet and sheet to protect exposed soil face
(optional)</p></li>
<li><p>15–20 large sized zip-lock bags per plot (27 x 33 cm; white block
for labelling)</p></li>
<li><p>Large plastic bag per plot to store individual samples together
(ca. 50 x 60 cm)</p></li>
<li><p>Voucher barcode labels (see the Generating Voucher Barcode Labels
for EMSA Specimens and Samples instruction sheet)</p></li>
<li><p>Permanent marker</p></li>
<li><p>Pit tape (2 m)</p></li>
<li><p>Spray bottle with deionised water</p></li>
<li><p>Towel (for cleaning equipment and hands)</p></li>
<li><p>Soil sieve (2 mm) and base tray</p></li>
<li><p>Hand lens (x10 magnification)</p></li>
<li><p>pH kit based on the specifications of Raupach and Tucker (1959)
(portable pH meters may also be used)</p></li>
<li><p>Electrical conductivity meter</p></li>
<li><p>1 Molar HCl (for testing effervescence in the field)</p></li>
<li><p>Deionised water</p></li>
<li><p>Australian Soil and Land Classification Handbook (Yellow Book;
NCST 2009)</p></li>
<li><p>Munsell Soil Colour Charts (Munsell Color 2009)</p></li>
<li><p>The Australian Soil Classification (Isbell and The National
Committee on Soil and Terrain 2021).</p></li>
</ul>"""^^rdf:HTML ;
    tern:instructions """<h3 id="instructions-and-procedures-3">Instructions and Procedures</h3>
<ol type="1">
<li><p>Ensure the <a href="https://linked.data.gov.au/def/nrm/d15d05db-5007-411e-b257-105ef4f76821">Plot Selection and Layout Module</a> has been completed to
mark out the plot boundary and define the current plot and visit in the
Monitor app.</p></li>
</ol>
<ol start="2" type="1">
<li><p>Select the Soils Module and then the Soil site observation and
pit characterisation protocol.</p></li>
<li><p>Select ‘field’ for the <em>survey variant</em>. The <em>start
date</em> will be automatically recorded.</p></li>
<li><p>Record the <em>observers</em>. Select existing observers from the
dropdown list or enter new ones.</p></li>
<li><p>The app will automatically record the <em>soil pit
ID</em>.</p></li>
<li><p>Traverse the core plot to familiarise yourself with the
homogeneity in respect to landform and soils.</p></li>
<li><p>Locate the site for the soil pit, navigate to outside the
southwest corner of the plot and assess whether the location best
represents the soil of the plot and is a suitable location for the soil
pit. If this is not the case, move to a better representative location
within the plot, taking care not to obstruct other concurrent survey
tasks.</p></li>
<li><p>Press the <em>choose on map</em> button to record soil sample pit
<em>location</em>. Record the <em>collection method</em> used to record
the location (e.g. differential GNSS).</p></li>
<li><p>Record a brief <em>location description</em> (i.e. a general
description to assist with re-location using distances and direction to
landmarks, where the soil site is located in respect to the plot, where
the soil pit is sitting within the context of the landscape, surrounding
vegetation community).</p></li>
</ol>
<h4 id="soil-site-observation">Soil site observation</h4>
<ol start="10" type="1">
<li><p>Consider a 20 m radius around the soil pit as the soil site
observation, using the Yellow Book as a reference source, complete
landform element and land surface fields:</p></li>
</ol>
<ul>
<li><p><em>Means of evaluation</em> – select from a dropdown list how
the slope will be measured.</p></li>
<li><p><em>Slope percent –</em> express slope tangent as a percentage
using up to three significant figures (e.g. 1%, 2.45%, 12.5%, 115%; see
<a href="#measuring-slope">Additional guidelines</a>).</p></li>
<li><p><em>Slope class -</em> automatically generated once the slope
percentage is entered.</p></li>
<li><p><em>Morphological type</em> and <em>inclination of slope</em> –
select from dropdown lists.</p></li>
<li><p><em>Landform element</em> – select from dropdown list. The
landform element at the soil site observation level may differ from the
plot description landform element.</p></li>
<li><p><em>Location within landform element</em> – the vertical position
of the soil pit within the height of the landform element.</p></li>
<li><p><em>Condition of surface soil when dry</em> – select from
dropdown list.</p></li>
<li><p><em>Disturbance</em> – select from dropdown list.</p></li>
</ul>
<ol start="11" type="1">
<li><p>Consider a 20 m radius around the soil pit as the soil site
observation, using the Yellow Book as a reference source, complete land
surface observations. Select the checkbox(s) against the land surface
features that are present at the soil site observation, this will limit
the fields to enter only those that are applicable:</p></li>
</ol>
<ul>
<li><p><em>Microrelief</em> – relief up to a few metres above the plane
of the land surface. Assess and record the <em>type</em>, <em>vertical
interval distance</em> (m) and <em>horizontal interval distance</em>
(m). Record the <em>proporation of gilgai components</em> for gilgai
microrelief types. Record the <em>agent</em> and <em>component
sampled</em> if ‘biotic’ is selected for the microrelief type. Record
multiple microrelief types if present.</p></li>
<li><p><em>Erosion</em> – accelerated or induced erosion rather than
natural erosion. Assess and record the <em>state</em>, <em>type</em> and
<em>severity</em>. Record multiple if present.</p></li>
<li><p><em>Surface coarse fragments</em> – assess and record the
<em>abundance</em>, <em>size</em>, <em>shape</em>, <em>lithology</em>,
<em>strength</em> and <em>alteration</em>. Record multiple if
present.</p></li>
<li><p><em>Rock outcrop</em> – assess and record the <em>abundance</em>
and <em>lithology</em>.</p></li>
</ul>
<ol start="12" type="1">
<li><p>Record any additional observations in the soil pit observation
<em>comments</em>.</p></li>
<li><p>Complete the soil site observations and continue to the soil pit
characterisation.</p>
<p>Soil pit characterisation</p></li>
</ol>
<p>Refer to the Yellow Book for further descriptions on all field codes
and descriptions.</p>
<ol start="14" type="1">
<li><p>Record the <em>observation type</em> used to expose the soil
profile.</p></li>
<li><p>Dig a soil pit to 1 m+ deep or to depth of limiting layer. Place
the spoil on a ground sheet to minimise disturbance and assist
backfilling. Record the <em>soil pit depth</em> (m). See <a href="#soil-pit-characterisation">Additional guidelines</a>.</p></li>
<li><p>If a depth of 1 m+ cannot be achieved, record what digging was
<em>stopped by</em>.</p></li>
<li><p>Assess which face of the pit is best for photographing, taking
into consideration angle of the sun and shadows. Position the pit tape
on the left or right edge of the best face and <em>add pit photo</em>
using your device's camera. Alternatively, an external camera can be
used to take the photo (see <a href="#soil-pit-characterisation">Additional guidelines</a>). Record any
additional pit <em>comments</em>. Assess and identify the soil horizons
in the soil profile.</p></li>
<li><p>Record the <em>horizon</em>, including a <em>numeric prefix</em>,
<em>horizon subdivision</em> and <em>horizon suffix</em> if relevant. If
‘M’ is selected for <em>horizon</em>, record the <em>deposition
mechanism</em>. Refer to the Soil Profile section in the Yellow Book and
the <a href="#horizons">Additional guidelines</a> below for further
descriptions. A preliminary horizon can be given at this point and may
be edited after the profile is described.</p></li>
<li><p>Record the <em>upper depth</em> (m) and <em>lower depth</em> (m)
of the soil horizon.</p></li>
<li><p>Assess the boundary between the horizon being assessed and the
horizon below, recording <em>boundary distinctness</em> and <em>boundary
shape</em>.</p></li>
<li><p>Assess and record <em>field texture</em>, including the
<em>grade, qualification</em> and <em>modifier.</em></p></li>
<li><p>Assess the <em>colour</em> of the soil in the horizon using the
Munsell Soils Color Charts (Munsell Color 2009). Record the <em>moisture
status</em> of the soil and the <em>hue</em>, <em>value</em> and
<em>chroma</em>. Moist and dry colours can be recorded (see <a href="#soil-colour">Additional guidelines</a>).</p></li>
<li><p>Select the checkbox(s) against the features that are present in
the horizon, this will limit the fields to enter to only those that are
applicable to the horizon:</p></li>
</ol>
<ul>
<li><p><em>Mottles</em> – assess and record the <em>type</em>,
<em>abundance</em>, <em>size</em>, <em>contrast</em>, <em>colour</em>
and <em>boundary distinctness</em>. Record multiple if present.</p></li>
<li><p><em>Coarse fragments</em> – assess and record the
<em>abundance</em>, <em>size</em>, <em>shape</em>, <em>lithology</em>,
<em>strength</em>, <em>alteration</em> and <em>distribution</em>. Record
multiple if present.</p></li>
<li><p><em>Structure</em> – assess and record the <em>grade of
pedality</em>, <em>size of peds</em>, <em>type of pedality</em> and
<em>compound pedality</em>. Record multiple if present (i.e. largest
peds parting to smaller sized peds down to the primary ped).</p></li>
<li><p><em>Segregation</em> – assess and record the <em>abundance</em>,
<em>nature</em>, <em>form</em>, <em>size</em>, <em>strength</em> and
<em>magnetic attributes</em>. Record multiple if present.</p></li>
<li><p><em>Voids</em> – assess and record the <em>width of cracks</em>,
<em>abundance of medium and coarse macropores</em>, <em>abundance of
very fine and fine macropores</em> and <em>macropore diameter</em>.
Record multiple if present.</p></li>
<li><p><em>Pans</em> – assess and record the <em>cementation</em>,
<em>type</em>, <em>continuity</em> and <em>structure</em>.</p></li>
<li><p><em>Cutans</em> – assess and record the <em>type</em>,
<em>abundance</em> and <em>distinctness</em>.</p></li>
<li><p><em>Roots</em> - assess and record the <em>abundance</em> and
<em>size</em>.</p></li>
</ul>
<ol start="24" type="1">
<li><p>Assess and record <em>consistence</em>, including the <em>soil
water status</em>, <em>strength of soil</em>, <em>stickiness</em> and
<em>plasticity type</em>.</p></li>
<li><p>Conduct the following field tests on soil collected from the
horizon:</p></li>
</ol>
<ul>
<li><p><em>Effervescence</em> – assess and record the effervescence of
carbonate in fine earth using 2–3 drops of 1 Molar HCl.</p></li>
<li><p><em>Field pH</em> – assess and record the pH in the field (to 0.5
of a unit) using a pH kit based on the specifications of Raupach and
Tucker (1959). Portable pH meters may also be used.</p></li>
<li><p><em>Electrical conductivity</em> (EC) - assess and record EC 1:5
using a portable EC meter. Follow instructions for the particular meter
being used</p></li>
</ul>
<ol start="26" type="1">
<li><p>Repeat steps 18–25 for each soil horizon down the soil profile,
select the + button to add soil horizon. When all horizons have been
entered, select complete soil horizon observations. The app will display
a summary of the horizons to assist with soil classification.</p></li>
<li><p>Assess and record the <em>Australian Soil Classification</em>
(ASC), including the <em>confidence level</em>, <em>order</em>,
<em>suborder</em>, <em>great group</em>, <em>subgroup</em> and
<em>family</em> level. Refer to the third edition of <em>The Australian
Soil Classification</em> for further descriptions (Isbell and The
National Committee on Soil and Terrain 2021).</p>
<p>Assess and record the soil water regime, including <em>soil
permeability</em> and <em>drainage</em> (that would likely occur in most
years), the <em>substrate lithology</em>, <em>depth of R horizon</em>
(m) if known and any additional <em>soil profile comments</em>.</p></li>
<li><p>Select <em>complete soil pit characterisation</em> to save and
continue to soil sampling.</p></li>
</ol>
<h4 id="soil-pit-sampling">Soil pit sampling</h4>
<ol start="29" type="1">
<li><p>Prepare a soil sample zip-lock bags for each 10 cm soil depth
increment. Use a permanent marker to write the plot code, date of
collection and soil depth increment. (see <a href="#sample-labelling">Sample labelling</a> for instructions on
assigning sample barcodes post-trip).</p></li>
<li><p>For each 10 cm soil depth increment, collect a 500 g soil sample
and place into the labelled zip-lock bag. Use the pit tape to determine
the increments (see <a href="#soil-samples-1">Additional
guidelines</a>). Depending on the depth of the horizon, more than one 10
cm sample can be taken from a horizon. Avoid collecting samples across
horizons.</p></li>
<li><p>Store all samples together in a large plastic bag labelled with
plot code and date of collection.</p></li>
<li><p>Select the complete the soil site observation and pit
characterisation button to queue the collection for submission.</p></li>
<li><p>If you are collecting bulk density samples, prior to backfilling
the soil pit undertake the <a href="#soil-bulk-density">Soil bulk
density protocol</a>, which collects soil bulk density samples from an
edge of the pit.</p></li>
</ol>"""^^rdf:HTML ;
